Which of the following is the correct restriction map?

answer.text: Both of the above

questiontext.text:
You digest a 4.5 kb plasmid with SpeI + KpnI. You also digest the same plasmid with SpeI and KpnI alone. After running the digests on a gel electrophoresis stained with SYBR safe alongside undigested plasmid you see the below banding pattern:-

answer.text: Both of the above

questiontext.text:
You have directionally cloned a 900 bp fragment of the human angiotensin I converting enzyme (ACE) gene into a 1.8 Kb plasmid using SpeI and PstI 'sticky ends'. A functional polymorphism linked to performance in East African endurance runners can occur within the cloned region of the ACE gene. This polymorphism also introduces a BamHI restriction site. Look at the below gel showing the BamHI single digest, SpeI + PstI double digest, and BamHI + SpeI + PstI triple digest.

The presence of the BamHI site indicates the likely presence of the performance linked polymorphism in this individual. Which of the following is the correct restriction map?

answer.text: Both of the above

feedback.text: From the fragment sizes in this gel we cannot distinguish between the 2 maps

questiontext.text:
You clone an 800 bp fragment which includes the Green Fluorescent Protein (GFP) gene into a 2.6 kb fragment. You digest the resulting plasmid with the following enzymes, the fragment sizes observed on an agarose gel are given alongside the enzyme:-

EcoRV: 1.6 kb, 1.8 kb

XhoI: 1.6 kb, 1.8 kb

EcoRV + XhoI: 0.6 kb, 0.8 kb, 1 kb Which of the following plasmid maps is correct?

You digest a 7.2 kb plasmid with EcoRI + SpeI. You also digest the plasmid with both EcoRI and SpeI alone. Below are the fragment sizes which correspond to these digests.

EcoRI: 2 kb, 2.6 kb

SpeI: 2.8 kb, 4.4 kb

EcoRI + SpeI: 0.8 kb, 1 kb, 1.2 kb, 1.6 kb, 2.6 kb Which of the following restriction maps is correct?

You digest a 3.6 kb plasmid with KpnI + HindIII. You expect that this digest will 'release' a 1.6 kb gene you have cloned into a 2 kb plasmid. You used KpnI and HindIII sticky ends to 'clone in' the 1.6 kb gene. Below is a gel showing KpnI, HindIII, and KpnI + HindIII digests alongside undigested plasmid.

Which of the following statements is most likely true?

answer.text: Your 3.6 kb fragment does not have a HindIII restriction site.
You are hopeless at pipetting and have not added HindIII enzyme into the single or double digest.
The HindIII enzyme has been maltreated in a previous use and is no longer functional. Use a fresh aliquot and try these digests once more.
all of the above

Which of the following maps is correct?

You digest a 4.2 kb plasmid with BamHI + XbaI. You also digest the plasmid with these enzymes on their own and run all the digests alongside 'uncut' plasmid. You see some unexpected results in the below gel. Which of the statements which follow best describes what you are seeing in the gel?

answer.text: BamHI is incompletely digesting the plasmid.
BamHI is not functional whatsoever; it should 'cut' the plasmid but hasn't. Discard this batch and try once more with a fresh aliquot.
There is no restriction site for BamHI in this plasmid.
none of the above

questiontext.text:
You are interested in a strange adaptation that arises in the Koala which makes it resistant to Chlamydia. You have found an association of this new trait to a functional polymorphism in a gene for a cell surface receptor. The polymorphism also introduces a NheI restriction site. You clone a 1.2 kb fragment from that gene into a 3.2 kb plasmid using XhoI and HindIII 'sticky ends'. Your plasmid also has a NheI restriction site within its 3.2 kb 'backbone'. You perform a number of digests on the clone. Below are the bands you see on a gel:XhoI: 4.4 kb

HindIII: 4.4 kb

NheI: 2 kb, 2.4 kb

XhoI + HindIII: 1.2 kb, 3.2 kb

NheI + XhoI + HindIII: 0.4 kb, 0.8 kb, 1.2 kb, 2 kb Which of the following restriction maps is correct?

You digest a 10.4 kb plasmid with SpeI + EcoRI + BamHI. You also digest with these enzymes singly. Below are the bands seen on a prestained SYBR safe gel after the gel has been run.

SpeI: 2.8 kb, 7.6 kb

EcoRI: 2 kb, 4 kb, 4.4 kb BamHI: 4.8 kb, 5.6 kb SpeI + EcoRI + BamHI: 1 kb, 1.3 kb, 1.5 kb, 1.8 kb, 2 kb Which of the following restriction maps is correct?
Which of the following plasmids will migrate the most quickly on an agarose electrophoresis gel?

answer.text: 2kb, linear
4kb, linear
6kb, linear
8kb, coiled

questiontext.text: Which of the following plasmids will migrate the most slowly on an agarose electrophoresis gel?

answer.text: 6kb, coiled
6kb, linear
4kb, coiled
4kb, linear

questiontext.text: On an agarose electrophoresis gel, which of these plasmids will migrate most quickly?

answer.text: 2kb, linear
3kb, coiled
3kb, supercoiled
3kb, linear
